# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1792-united-states-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] The first midterm elections were held in the United States in 1790 and 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] They occurred in the middle of President George Washington's first term, and determined the members of the 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Formal political parties did not exist, but Congress was broadly divided between a faction supporting the policies of the Washington administration and a faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Despite modest gains for the anti-administration faction, the pro-administration faction retained control of both houses of Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Vermont and Kentucky joined the union during the 2nd Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the House, neither faction made significant gains or losses, and the pro-administration faction retained control of the chamber.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the anti-administration faction picked up a moderate number of seats, but the pro-administration faction narrowly retained control of the chamber.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 3rd United States Congress, in 1792 and 1793.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Congress was broadly divided between a Pro-Administration faction supporting the policies of George Washington's administration and an Anti-Administration faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Due to this, the Federalist Party (generally overlapping with the Pro-Administration faction) and the Democratic-Republican Party (generally overlapping with the Anti-Administration faction) were starting to emerge as the distinct political parties of the First Party System.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In this election, the Pro-Administration faction maintained control of the Senate, but lost its majority in the House.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, incumbent President George Washington was re-elected without any major opposition.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington had considered retirement, but was convinced to seek re-election for the purpose of national unity.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Though Washington went unchallenged, Governor George Clinton of New York sought to unseat John Adams as vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Adams received the second most electoral votes, and so was re-elected to office.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the House, 37 seats were added following the 1790 census.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction picked up several seats, narrowly taking the majority from the Pro-Administration faction.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Frederick Muhlenberg, who leaned closer to the Pro-Administration faction, was elected Speaker of the House.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Anti-Administration faction picked up one seat, but the Pro-Administration faction maintained a small majority.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:1792-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
